fic institutional factors and universal constraints on actors, which emanate from characteristics of the global warming problem itself. It also considers how corporatist institutional characteristics may make a difference in attaining sustainable development. Overall this book provides a new set of comparisons of climate policy and new frameworks of analysis, which could be built on in future research on cross-national climate policy analysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnvironmental policyzGreat Britain. 0aEnvironmental policyzJapan. 0aEnvironmental policy-Great Britain. 0aEnvironmental policy-Japan. 0aGlobal warming. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh  aBritain.  aClimate action.  aJapan.  aclimate policy.  acorporatist institutional characteristics.  adecision-making.  aglobal warming.  agovernment-industry relations.  ainstitutional factors.  ainstitutions.  asustainable development.1 aOshitani, Shizuka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779228040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792280423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792280/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles